\f2\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 What the Ackerer, Hugonnier & Jermann Mathematics Actually Does\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 At its core, the framework does 
\f2\b three things
\f0\b0  mathematically:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 1. It proves perpetual contracts have a unique, arbitrage-free price without interest.
\f0\b0  The no-bubble + integrability conditions guarantee that 
\f3\fs26 f_t = 
\f4 \uc0\u954 
\f3 /(
\f4 \uc0\u954 
\f3  + r_b - r_a) \'d7 x_t
\f0\fs24  is the 
\f1\i only valid price
\f0\i0 . This isn't an approximation \'97 it's a proof.\

\f2\b 2. It provides a random time representation.
\f0\b0  The price of a perpetual equals the expected spot price at a random exponential stopping time \uc0\u952 . This is profound: it means a perpetual is mathematically equivalent to a 
\f1\i lottery over future spot prices
\f0\i0 , with a precise density.\

\f2\b 3. It extends to payoff functions via Theorem 6/Proposition 6.
\f0\b0  Any payoff 
\f4\fs26 \uc0\u966 
\f3 (x_t)
\f0\fs24  can be priced perpetually \'97 calls, puts, nonlinear payoffs \'97 with Black-Scholes-like closed forms via power solutions to a PDE.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

