\f0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 The price of the instrument is simply the 
\f2\b expected value of the underlying asset at a random redemption time
\f0\b0 , with no discounting at an interest rate. The "discounting" is entirely absorbed into the probability distribution of \uc0\u952  \'97 how likely the event is to happen sooner vs later \'97 which is determined by \u954  alone.\
This is a profound shift. You're not discounting future cash flows at a rate of return. You're asking: 
\f1\i what is the fair expected value of what you'll receive, given a precise probabilistic model of when you'll receive it?
\f0\i0  That is fundamentally a different question \'97 and one that doesn't require interest.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
