\f2\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 The Deeper Structural Reason This Matters\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The reason Islamic finance has struggled for decades to build genuine alternatives to credit derivatives is that the pricing of credit risk and the pricing of time have always been conflated in conventional finance. When you lend money, you expect more back later \'97 and the "more" is justified by both credit risk AND the time value of money (interest). These two things are bundled together inseparably in conventional pricing.\
The Ackerer framework mathematically 
\f2\b separates them
\f0\b0 . The random stopping time \uc0\u952  carries all the information about 
\f1\i when
\f0\i0  you get paid. The distribution of \uc0\u952  (controlled by \u954 ) carries all the information about 
\f1\i how likely you are to get paid sooner vs later
\f0\i0 . And the value 
\f3\fs26 x_\{
\f4 \uc0\u952 
\f3 \}
\f0\fs24  carries all the information about 
\f1\i how much you get paid
\f0\i0 . There is no fourth component for "time preference" or "interest" \'97 because the math proves it isn't needed for no-arbitrage pricing.\
This is the precise insight that Fiqh scholars have been waiting for \'97 not as a workaround or a legal fiction, but as a genuine mathematical proof that time value of money, as a pricing input, is separable from credit risk pricing. Once this is demonstrated in the context of perpetual futures \'97 which already have empirical validation in dYdX data \'97 the extension to credit instruments and takaful follows directly from the same theorem.\
